node.text:
A Saturday spectacular specimen! 💘 A fine Victorian home. All the heart eyes here 😍 Posted @withregram • @godzilla1950 At 214 S. State St…. You see an amazing house that you admire on the internet ….but when you see it in real life, it’s sooo surreal! ✨🌟This beautiful Stick Style/ QueenAnne with its polychromatic color scheme is a vision of loveliness framed by two towering trees. The house was built in 1889 for Ora Pelton, a physician & a surgeon. The manse is still privately owned. 

On vacation now to visit the beautiful state of Wisconsin, passing thru Elgin en route. Hopefully I’ll get to post some more great Victorians! 🙌 #victorian #victorianhouse #victorianarchitecture #victorianstyle #archi_ologie #archilovers #archilovers #theamericanhome #housestalker #houseaddict #oldhouselove #oldhouseenthusiast #iloveoldhouses #thisoldhouse  #historichouse #houseportrait #loveofoldhouses #midwest #beautifulhouseoldandnew #americancastlesff  #curbappeal #houses_phototrip #oldhousecharm  #houseoftheday

node.text:
No Name Thursday
Nola beauty 😍
Thanks for tagging #archi_ologie 
Reposted from @davidlhoste Circa 1850s raised center hall home in Faubourg West Bouligny. According to _New Orleans Architecture, Volume VII: Jefferson City (2010), it is one of only a few documented antebellum houses in the Uptown area. It was originally built on St. Charles Avenue at Bordeaux Street and was moved to its current location facing Bordeaux Street at its intersection with Pitt Street. In the 1880s or 90s it was updated, adding the Italianate detailing. #neworleans #architecture #bouligny

node.text:
Happy #mansardmonday y’all! 🤩 Posted @withregram • @nolaarchitecturetours Happy #mansardmonday ! 
This house was built for Bradish Johnson in 1872. With Italianate decorations capped by a Mansard roof, this is a great example of Second Empire Style Architecture.

Bradish Johnson was an industrialist who owned a distillery in NYC that was one of many accused of selling milk that had come from sick cows, referred to as “Swill Milk”. This milk was often altered with chalk, plaster, and flour and it led to high infant mortality rates in the city. When newspapers broke the story of swill milk, New York passed some of the first food safety laws that would lead to the Food and Drug Act in 1906.

Bradish Johnson also owned some Louisiana plantations including Woodland and Whitney. 

This house was built as his retirement property. Today it is the offices and library of the Louise McGehee School for girls.
*
